{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:09:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:09:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18068"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18068"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.19,0.57,0.05,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74989"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74989"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman with early-stage breast cancer is discussing treatment options with her healthcare team. She is concerned about the side effects of chemotherapy and radiation therapy, but also wants to ensure the best possible outcome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ethical principles best guides the assessment of treatment risks versus benefits in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Confidentiality","Autonomy","Beneficence","Justice","Non-maleficence"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ethical principle of \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-maleficence\u003C/strong\u003E means \u0027first, do no harm\u0027. This fundamental principle requires healthcare providers to consider the potential risks of their actions and avoid causing unnecessary harm. This is an essential component of good medical practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other ethical principles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConfidentiality\u003C/strong\u003E describes the obligation to protect private patient information and maintain trust in the therapeutic relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutonomy\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle of recognising and supporting a patient\u0027s right to make informed decisions about their own healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeneficence\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle of taking positive action to benefit patients and improve their health outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJustice\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle of ensuring fair and equitable distribution of healthcare resources and services.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-maleficence must often be balanced against other ethical principles, particularly beneficence, as many medical interventions carry some risk of harm but may provide greater potential benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-maleficence is the ethical principle of avoiding harm to patients, summarised by \u0027first, do no harm\u0027.","The principle of non-maleficence requires healthcare providers to consider and minimise potential risks of interventions.","Non-maleficence must be balanced against beneficence when making clinical decisions."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18068"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T16:46:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T16:46:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10782"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74989"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4947","links":{"se